Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro zone is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 euro zone countries, inflation in November was higher than expected - after October&#39;s 2.6 percent, the annual inflation rate was 3.1 percent, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have been for just 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the American, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered its key interest rate. In their opinion, the interest rate cut, the rising commodity prices and the slight drop in unemployment would encourage the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below 2 percent, or at least close to the 2 percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB finds itself in a quandary: inflation has to be &quot;agreed upon&quot; in order to rule out the need for action at a later date.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate in Germany reached a twelve-year record high in November; in Spain the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Rising food and energy prices are responsible for the increase in inflation in the euro zone.
MATIF wheat quotations rose 88 percent and soybean prices also hit a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in prices for edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world price of crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
Analysts are assuming a 3 percent inflation rate for the next 3-4 months, but put the annual average rate at 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect that the ECB will cut interest rates twice.
Gallup locates government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers grew significantly by early December. For the first time since 2002, the party has the largest base camp, while support for the Socialists has hit an all-time low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
Among voters loyal to the party, the difference is clear thanks to the high level of determination of the opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) opposed to a fifth (20 percent) approval for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry hurdle: they come to two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Overall economic sentiment has continued to deteriorate since the last low - the proportion of people who rate the country&#39;s economy as &quot;extremely bad&quot; has never been higher (41 percent), while another 46 percent said it was &quot;fairly bad&quot;. &quot; hold.
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about the change in their financial situation.
The majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate further in the coming year; only a tenth assumes an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents - a historic high - judged the prime minister&#39;s work to be &quot;more of a nuisance than good&quot;.
Thirteen percent of respondents have a high level of trust or general trust in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of the Fidesz party leader.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think dissatisfaction with the prime minister can be managed without a change of government.
After the riots last October, 35% said that the government and the head of government should remain in power. Today this proportion is only 20%, while the relative majority (33 percent) sees the only solution in new elections.
When asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent said they would &quot;certainly&quot; participate and another 20 percent would &quot;probably&quot; vote.
For comparison: if the parliamentary elections were held this Sunday, only 55 percent would &quot;certainly&quot; go to the polls, another 15% consider their participation &quot;probable&quot;. Given these tendencies, the outcome of the referendum would be predictable.
74% would vote against tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the daily hospital allowance.
Applied to the group of people who &quot;definitely&quot; took part in the referendum, the proportions of opponents of tuition, practice and hospital fees would even amount to 81, 84 and 89 percent respectively.
Auchan most expensive, Tesco increased by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trading area this year kept the average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that this year there was no increase in VAT.
Article from Napi Gazdaság
In the Budaörs Trade Triangle, the price of the usual Christmas basket &quot;Napi&quot; increased by 16 percent this year, however, price increases of over HUF 1,000 were recorded in all hypermarkets.
After the prices in the food markets &quot;galloped away&quot; last December, the percentage inflation was not drastic compared to the already high previous starting level.
However, consumers will certainly be put off by the fact that what they paid well under HUF 9,000 for last year is not even available for HUF 10,000 this year.
The price of the &quot;Napi&quot; basket exceeded the magic 10,000 HUF mark by at least 91 HUF in the examined markets.
The highest price was 10,573 HUF.
(In 6800 the price was 6,800 HUF.)
The prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at the previous year&#39;s level, while the prices for turkey breast fillets, nuts and poppy seeds rose sharply.
Prices for flour and bread corresponded to the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary, but at Auchan there was 1kg of bread rolls for 139 forints.
The price of the product did not fall below 200 forints due to competition.
Also surprising was the price of a two-liter Coca-Cola deposit bottle of less than 200 forints, so the drink including the deposit only cost 257 HUF.
Nevertheless, in this year&#39;s &quot;Napi&quot; shopping basket comparison, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
Our calculations show that Cora has increased prices in the &#39;Napi&#39; basket by 15 per cent compared to last year&#39;s Christmas prices, while Tesco and Auchan have each increased by 18 per cent.
The difference between last year&#39;s cheapest basket and this year&#39;s most expensive basket was 12%, while the increase between last year&#39;s cheapest basket and this year&#39;s most expensive basket was 21%.
The average price increase was 1,480.00 HUF.
The average price increase last year was 1,206.00 forints, but the increase in VAT had an impact on prices last Christmas.
It was precisely this process that hit the retail trade badly: Apparently, the department stores could not quite decide which price range to apply to the individual articles, since the effects of the price increase on consumer behavior were unpredictable.
(If the retailer misplans the velocity of a product, he can lose substantial profits in the price range that varies with traffic intensity.)
Due to VAT, the increase in price of the &quot;Napi&quot; basket last year was so radical that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 forints, while the price difference for the cheapest basket was only 844 forints.
Such extremes were not observed this year, as the most expensive basket cost HUF 1,630.00 more than last year, and even the cheapest basket increased by HUF 1,284.00.
A comparison of the last two Christmas seasons showed a catastrophic price increase, the price of daily consumables in hypermarkets has risen by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, in turn, does not necessarily corroborate data from the Central Statistical Office of Hungary: for some staple foods, the Statistical Office found inflation of more than 30 percent over a 12-month period.
In addition to flour, this also applies to eggs.)
However, if you take a look at the &quot;Napi&quot; shopping cart, this seems almost impossible for the latter, since the price level of the product, which was already expensive last year, has risen by hardly more than 10 percent, even in the worst case.
Flour suppliers are obviously in a stronger position than egg suppliers - after all, they were able to pass the drastic price increase onto the multinationals.
In the golden trading triangle, the hypermarkets don&#39;t complain; There are constant reports of good years.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores no longer look at the prices.
Large quantities of everything are bought, long-life groceries go over the counters in pallets.
On Wednesday morning there were endless queues at the checkout in all three department stores when the number of customers suddenly exploded.
However, the country is reporting lower footfall, with many multinationals complaining to pollsters that they may not even be able to meet their target sales, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
In many places, savings are being made on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals that were due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overloading of the staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to containing the infections, according to the senior doctor at the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, savings are also being made on disinfectants.
MRSA infection was recently diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The man injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but the man had to return shortly afterwards with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not yet been performed because of the bacterium that is still in the patient&#39;s body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1,094 infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens had been reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System from hospitals, according to the senior physician at the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were definitely registered in the hospitals, but the number of unreported cases is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, Staphylococcus aureus, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
About a third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium in their nose without causing disease.
SA-related infections (such as strep throat, tonsillitis, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics and are easily curable.
However, if the doses of the agents are too high or used improperly, the well-responding bacteria develop into antibiotic-resistant bacteria, which spread quickly under the right conditions in the hospitals.
These bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infections or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis, particularly in patients with a weakened or permanently poorly functioning immune system, but also in elderly patients or patients with low body weight.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday hospital life.
The infection shouldn&#39;t be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA only doesn&#39;t exist where people aren&#39;t looking for it.
Resistant to antibiotics
&quot;Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks when they are cared for, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment&quot; - says Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are checked for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too infrequent
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for containing the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients admitted and immediately isolate those infected with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not so common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this examination from the state health insurance.
Most cases therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and clinical pictures.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the agent from developing, although hospitals do not always comply with this directive.
According to Karolina Böröcz, microbiological sampling is even rarer among outpatients or those in primary care.
Savings are made on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by caregivers.
This is precisely why washing hands or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, the rooms are often overcrowded, the beds are closely spaced, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, it is unfortunately the case in hospitals that are less well off financially that savings are even made on disinfectants, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that actually promote the development of infections.
Such infections are demonstrably far less frequent there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes enormous costs for the health insurance companies, which is why they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
According to the first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the tendency of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Center for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has made preventing the emergence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and preventing infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
Death Driver Sheriff wasn&#39;t drunk
In the case of the police chief of the XXII. District caused car accident with fatal outcome is now the official report.
The now resigned chief of police of the XXII. District, who killed a pedestrian in a car accident on Tuesday, was not under the influence of alcohol or drugs, Attila Morvai, the spokesman for Budapest&#39;s chief prosecutor&#39;s office, said on Friday after the official report on the case was presented.
