Another EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) signed three loan agreements with a total value of EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday. The money should flow into education, traffic and environmental protection infrastructure and the energy industry.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for financing transport and environmental protection projects that are being implemented with grants from the Cohesion Fund. The loan agreement for EUR 100 million was signed earlier, the current agreement is about the use of the EUR 200 million.
The sum of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement is also to be used for the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300m for this purpose in Hungary; The use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later as part of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the parties have signed an agreement for EUR 50 million, which will mainly go to research and development programs at the University of Debrecen.
The subway line 4 was also discussed at the meeting.
It was agreed that once Hungary has clarified the details of the metro financing with the EU, the original contract and possible modifications will be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary with a total value of EUR 8.4 billion.
The loan interest is EURIBOR-bound, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, commission-free.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all of Europe is paying close attention to the previously rarely mentioned Balkan country.
What, where, and who buys in what is still the cheapest market in the EU, which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most sought-after place for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe at the moment, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Between the mountains, the most popular are the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa, by the sea Albena, the &quot;Gold Coast&quot;, the &quot;Sun Coast&quot; and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar are the most popular, but real estate is located around Kavarna and Balcik also more and more in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later the interior will also attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and the extremely cheap area of Russe will also see more buyers.
The capital Sofia also has tempting offers - retail and office space offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on the way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfing paradises, attracting tourists in both the summer and winter seasons as well as the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy property in Bulgaria are also looking to change their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while the Black Sea and ski resorts have predominantly Russian buyers.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgiy Yankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down either buy revitalized properties around 50-100,000 euros, or run-down houses around 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connections and accessibility as well as communication options are very important, but proximity to a large city, shops and doctors are also crucial for buyers.
The second category includes those looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations for Germans in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of increasing value in the medium to long term.
However, real estate in the capital is becoming more and more expensive due to the ever-growing demand.
Although property prices in Bulgaria are the lowest in the EU, prices have risen by 21 percent annually over the past five years.
The increase in property prices far outstrips the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percents
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced that the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali roadmap, which defines the emission-reducing measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
A fierce debate is currently underway between industrialized and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate specific figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
The other big question at the conference is whether the industrialized countries are willing to support the developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on assistance to developing countries was also reached.
The adjustment fund, which is subject to the Kyoto Protocol, is to be administered by a 16-member council, presumably at the UN&#39;s Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be read in &quot;Piac és Profit&quot;.
Hungary&#39;s six percent
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU&#39;s efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate protection measures and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister stated that the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured from 1990 levels), regardless of whether the &#39;post-2012 deal&#39; is achieved or not. The Union would even be willing to advocate a 30 percent reduction, provided that other large industrialized countries in the world or developing countries are also willing to fulfill their obligations responsibly and to the best of their ability.
Gábor Fodor emphasized that the target of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of just 5.2 percent, while the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed itself to a minus of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a target the country will certainly meet, according to the Environment Ministry&#39;s press release.
The stakes are high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement has to be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction projects laid down in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed by a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also emphasized by the IPCC, the international scientific committee on climate change of the UN, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize, in its most recent report.
This would delay emission reductions and make it inevitable that the earth&#39;s average temperature would rise by more than 2°C, with extremely serious and irreversible consequences, according to scientists.
British Army advertises on YouTube
British Army units posted footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: since March 2006, special units stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations conducted against the Taliban to the Internet, reports the BBC.
Filmed with miniature cameras mounted on helmets, the footage is checked at Kandahar Air Force Base and then sent to London, where it will be posted on the internet.
Political message unavoidable
Luftwaffe soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, and their &quot;channel&quot; has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered under &quot;defenceheadquarters&quot; in spring 2007 to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the British Foreign Office (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
The Air Force originally published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and the Department of Defense says the posts also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of the foreign missions.
Propaganda released in this way is almost free of charge compared to traditional television advertising, defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain level of political message, as they in their own way confirm the raison d&#39;être of the military measures decided upon by the government.
Americans advertise with game
However, the army also has to fight against amateur footage that, along with the carefully edited, censored footage, also makes it onto the Internet - such as those showing the death of the soldiers: the somewhat hypocritical, &quot;official&quot; propaganda films only talk about the casualties, however, the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Incidentally, numerous videos shot in action from the theaters of war in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British only recently discovered this &quot;genre&quot; for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game &quot;America&#39;s Army&quot;, in which the player can slip into the skin of the soldier within the framework of a more or less lifelike simulation.
