One hundred guests are invited to Vajdahunyad Castle in City Park (&quot;Városliget&quot;); according to information from the department, the expenses are measured at 1,000 forints per guest.
As the press department reports, it will be a very simple reception, to which only foreign diplomats accredited in Hungary will be invited.
The receptions, which are held every year, traditionally begin with a short speech by the minister and end with a restrained feast.
As reported by the relevant press offices on [origo] request, there will be no Christmas celebrations either at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs or at the Ministry of Education.
When asked about the cost of the Christmas party, the press department of the Ministry of the Environment was unable to provide any information.
In any case, more than 400 guests were invited to the celebration, which is being held in the Kunstgewerbemuseum.
More and more forces mobilized for a giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Trade Union Federation formed their coordinating committee on Friday for the indefinite strike that begins on Monday.
A large protest meeting will be held on Saturday, and work stoppages will begin on Monday - the day of the referendum on the health insurance law.
Significant traffic delays caused by the strike are expected, as rail traffic will be almost completely stopped, and the Budapest public transport company (BKV) will also be on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of Monday&#39;s strike will be announced jointly by the League of Unions and the Federation of Unions on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee will also be established, which will be responsible for coordinating Monday&#39;s actions.
A mass protest meeting will be held on Saturday and from Monday all organizations that have joined the strike will be on hold indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike that started on the day of the parliamentary vote on the health insurance law was not defined.
If the National Council does not accept the health insurance law, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet to discuss how to proceed.
Due to the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that the vote on the health insurance law will only take place later in the evening, or even at midnight.
The strikes beginning on Monday will result in significant traffic disruptions: the railway workers will stop working for an indefinite period of time, and in the morning most public transport and more than half of the Volán companies will be at a standstill.
At the same time, there will be motorway closures in one direction in many places.
Numerous trade unions and civil organizations followed the call for a strike - the list of participants is continuously updated on the league website.
Some organizations have announced strikes for an indefinite period, while others are planning a temporary work stoppage.
As of Thursday afternoon, no agreement could be reached between the Hungarian Railways MÁV and the Free Union of Railway Workers VDSZSZ on adequate services, although more and more people are traveling by train around the Christmas holidays.
According to previous reports, there will be strikes at the BKV from the start of operations until 1 p.m., at Budapest Airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the LIGA trade unions for electricity and heat energy will stop working for four hours, and the teachers&#39; union bwz. the Democratic Teachers&#39; Union have called for 2 and 2-8 hour strikes respectively.
The Hungarian Medical Association strikes alternately at different times across the country, the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Welfare Workers, a sub-organization of the SZEF, the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the league is that the government withdraw the draft health insurance reform and present a new concept for social discourse.
The second requirement concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due next year.
Demand number three is that the professional groups entitled to claim should have access to the early retirement system before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which belongs to the League of Trade Unions, did not accept the offer made by the Ministry of Transport concerning the secondary lines and is now demanding a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases sovereign risk
According to Political Capital&#39;s Risk Analyzing Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, established this August with the support of the &quot;Movement for a Better Hungary&quot;, have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute&#39;s &quot;Risk Warning Report&quot; states, among other things: In connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guards, the highest political risk represents the &quot;exacerbation of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which even in the short term can become violent could lead to ethnic disputes&quot;.
According to the research institute, the main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guards, which is probably aimed at provoking such a confrontation.
As reported, this is seen as an omission on the part of the political leaders: &quot;Public figures have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups who have now based their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary antagonism&quot;.
It is believed that this would exacerbate the problem, make rational dialogue impossible, favor extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guards, not least thanks to the enormous attention from the domestic and foreign media, have &quot;significantly damaged Hungary&#39;s image abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity&quot;.
We remember: since autumn 2006 the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been on the upswing, so that since summer 2007 several organizations calling themselves &quot;national self-defence associations&quot; have been founded.
