Holidays are not public holidays everywhere
In Hungary, public holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of rescheduling the working days around the public holidays has now become established, but the coming year will bring us fewer such days.
In the EU and America, too, &quot;holiday&quot; means something else.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and non-working days.
Non-working days are mostly church holidays or are related to important historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: Both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are non-working days - the latter alone so that those celebrating New Year&#39;s Eve can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen public holidays.
National holidays are March 15, commemorating the 1848 revolution, and October 23, commemorating the 1956 revolution.
The founding of the state is celebrated on August 20th, work is celebrated on May 1st, and we commemorate our dead on November 1st and 2nd.
In addition, there are two public holidays each at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of &quot;working day shifting&quot; has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
However, the price of the long weekends is that we have to work or go to school on the Saturdays before.
When this day, which falls before or after the public holiday, should ultimately be processed, has been determined for many years by the Minister of Labor in a separate ordinance.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, public employees and civil servants alike.
The only exceptions are companies and institutions in which operations continue without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays.
This year, the only thing that messes up the work regulations is the holidays at the end of the year: From December 24th, life in this country literally comes to a standstill, as most people take time off in lieu for the days between Christmas and New Year&#39;s Eve, or take the vacation that was specifically set aside for this purpose.
Next year there will be more public holidays in the middle of the week or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer rescheduling of the working days than this year.
The calendar is first &quot;turned upside down&quot; around Labor Day so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday April 26th will be a working day so that Friday May 2nd can be a rest day.
The second rescheduling is related to the public holiday on October 23: On Saturday, October 18, you will have to work through Friday, October 24 in advance.
However, the end of the year will be marked by the holidays after everything stops and stops from December 24th, even if New Year&#39;s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six deterrent little things to annoy co-workers
E-mails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice: they bring &quot;color&quot; to everyday life at work.
The only question is whether you get used to these small inconveniences, or do you better face the challenge and consciously try to avoid these misleading, annoying situations for others.
tips.
&quot;Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called,&quot; says a colleague.
Missing a meeting as a result?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it, perhaps by calling the marketing department and ruefully admitting you forgot to target the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, the matter is settled with an apology.
Before you get tangled up in embarrassing excuses, you should think about what you can do to create truly unpleasant moments for your colleagues and try to consciously avoid these situations.
Borrowed something that doesn&#39;t belong to you?
There&#39;s nothing more annoying than reaching for a document, stationery, or phone, but it&#39;s not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - is it gone this morning?
Or is the ballpoint pen you thought lost discovered on a colleague&#39;s desk?
You shouldn&#39;t borrow anything from your colleagues without asking, because they are right to get annoyed when they realize that something has been lost.
So, don&#39;t put any envelopes or post-its from the office in your pocket, because it could hit you: none left when you need them urgently.
Gossip about the private lives of colleagues?
There is no effective way to stop gossip that has already started.
Who did what with whom?
Where and why?
If possible, one should not foist information (or assumptions) about the private lives of colleagues on everyone!
And if someone does open up and reveals their innermost secret to us, we shouldn&#39;t abuse this trust!
It&#39;s best to be as silent as the grave instead of telling someone who isn&#39;t there, even if others also know about the colleague&#39;s problems.
Called in sick for no reason?
When you call the office to call in sick because you&#39;re unwell, citing a nagging headache, or you just want to rest, there&#39;s one thing to be clear about: your own work, urgent errands, projects with fixed ones Appointments now have to be made by colleagues instead of by yourself.
So don&#39;t play along badly with your colleagues!
If you already know the day before that you won&#39;t be able to make it to the office the next day, or that something could come up that will make you have to stay at home, you should report it in good time so that neither your colleagues nor your boss unexpectedly announce your absence be confronted.
Humming, giggling, talking on the phone
Are you engrossed in your work, but are suddenly disturbed by the loud giggling of your colleagues?
Unintentionally overheard a phone conversation that you shouldn&#39;t have heard?
Don&#39;t annoy co-workers with humming, chanting, loud conversations (held over their heads), stomping, constant scolding, or nagging.
All of this can be very disruptive, even if they are not engrossed in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Is it always the other person&#39;s fault?
If a project is not finished on time, if you have forgotten to send an important letter or important message, you should not blame others for your own forgetfulness!
If possible, you should not excuse yourself from the chaos in the office or the loud colleagues!
It is best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others were affected by them too!
The question of how to make up for the mistake or make up for lost time is only too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like at home?
Training pants and slippers: Comfortable for at home, but has no place in the office!
You shouldn&#39;t even dress so casually if the workplace actually allows it!
Just don&#39;t get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself enough to dress appropriately in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
