Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you want from your vacation, it will come true if you just choose the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea as calm as a pond.
Palm trees and all inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and beguiling cocktails on the beach.
Kite surfing, golf and roulette.
You&#39;ll find that in abundance on the islands of the Caribbean.
But you will only find so much more on one island, and that island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Greater Antilles.
At the time of the Spaniards, Cuba was their bastion for conquering America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana was once a warehouse or transit camp for treasures looted by the Spaniards in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the very end of the 20th century.
One of the bosses of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, had it built, because everything that was considered a crime in the USA (especially during Prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were among others
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
High-rise buildings grew in Havana, cars drove along the wide boulevards, which were among the cult symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and he had his yacht in Cojímar.
Show business stars and politicians from across America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
And today?
You too can leave your autograph on the walls of the Havana Bodeguita.
At the bar in the Hotel Nacional, cocktails are mixed for you according to your wishes.
And the cult cars of the 1950s still drive around in Havana to this day, because the once-imported shigulis and Fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty, humid air.
Havana, especially its oldest part, may be very run-down, but nowhere else in the area will you find so many wonderful colonial sights as right here.
Other places are being spruced up, for example Trinidad.
With tourism bringing much-needed money, this development was given the green light.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have appeared not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguín and also on islets such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba offers another quirk that is unique in the world and that attracts railway enthusiasts in particular.
The sugar cane from remote plantations was brought to the sugar factories by steam and diesel-powered narrow-gauge railways.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see cute and fully functioning locomotives whose contemporaries have long been in museums elsewhere.
destinations
Most of the visitors to Cuba do not miss the most important places.
So you no longer have to write in detail about Varadero or Havana.
Suffice it to say that there is a museum in the already mentioned Hemingway estate, which should not be missed if you like this writer.
The Viñales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, rise steeply from the valley floor, fertile soil has accumulated in their cavities, through which even weathered rock areas are covered with dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the finest Cuban tobacco is grown.
You can meet him in his final form if you visit one of Havana&#39;s cigar factories.
It may also be interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the TV series &quot;Major Zeman&quot; was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Trading in slaves and sugar brought her fame and fortune.
The wealth was embodied in the neat beauty of the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by later French settlers, has changed little in four hundred years.
Trinidad, nestled between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that as recently as the 1950s there was no road connecting the area to the rest of the country.
This isolation helped it go unnoticed.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was demolished either, everyone was happy that they had a roof over their heads.
If you have more than an afternoon in Trinidad, it is worth visiting interesting places in the area, such as Playa Ancón beach or the &quot;Valley of the Sugar Mills&quot;.
In the evening, go to the Casa de la Música, which comes alive after dark and where the music doesn&#39;t stop until morning.
Baracoa
This little town in the far east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
Certainly this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading there from Guantánamo have to overcome high and rugged mountains and pass through a landscape that has hardly been touched by human intervention.
UNESCO included this eastern outpost of Cuba in its World Heritage List thanks to its untouched nature.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in reality it was made about a hundred years after Columbus&#39; voyages), and from the hill where the former castle stands, the current Hotel El Castillo to see several mesas, of which El Yunque is the best known.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the Bay of Pigs and the Isla de Pinos island, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patroness Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion which the descendants of slaves profess, many pages could be written about all this.
But, as the saying goes: Better to see it with your own eyes.
