After being kept confidential for more than 60 years, the Bad Arolsen Nazi archives, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents in the archive, which are housed over a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be viewed until now, unless with a &quot;humanitarian&quot; intention, i.e. individual and name-related, i.e. when asked by a former victim or his Relatives.
In May 2006, the eleven states charged with administering them - including Germany, France, Israel and the USA - agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
sensitive information
