Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the mental handicap of some deportation victims.
The concentration camp inmate lists, or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo, were collected after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labor, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest, so that they could to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
However, part of the scientific community shows only limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
&quot;One should not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents,&quot; declared Prof. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
