New fears over gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is brewing between Ukraine and Russia, raising the risk that Russian fuel exports to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of Russia&#39;s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are routed through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kyiv has warned that if Moscow increases the price it pays for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous conflict between the two states last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest row between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia&#39;s state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine must be billed more as the company has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom&#39;s imports.
&quot;It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit countries in talks,&quot; Ukraine&#39;s Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters.
&quot;Changing natural gas prices should no doubt be coupled with our arguments about the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.&quot;
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This subsequently led to a drop in exports to Western Europe, driving up prices drastically.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union&#39;s supply.
Russia has the world&#39;s largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
