Once it&#39;s clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he doesn&#39;t even have to be around long, that respite is over: public services begin to leak; the cabinet ministers begin to chatter; the press looks for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown&#39;s position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would like to disown Tony Blair, he was his first lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction records, for example, are related to decisions Brown made as Chancellor of the Treasury.
