The new fuss over political donations is a good example.
The garboesque Abrahams, who compares his donations to his charitable offerings, says he doesn&#39;t want public recognition for his goodwill.
That may be the case, but it wasn&#39;t up to him to decide.
The laws against anonymity for major political contributors are clear, and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those running the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham&#39;s agreement but not that it&#39;s illegal, will of course have to ask himself some questions; as did Jon Mendlesohn, Labour&#39;s chief financial collector, who was told about the odd donations in October.
But so far Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest he knew about these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the prime minister has done half the work.
He was quick to condemn his party&#39;s violation of the law, but he watered down that resolve by reaching for a well-known instrument, a committee of inquiry into the issue - led to top it all off by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the &quot;lessons to be learned&quot; are not very complicated.
If the law has been broken, it&#39;s a matter for the police.
That being said, there are other things Mr. Brown needs to do, like finding a permanent chair for the independent Committee on Public Life Standards, which has been vacant for six months, and moving forward with sweeping reform of political party funding.
That would require Labor hardliners to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly abandon the special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a party comrade like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win voters back; and the only way he can achieve victory is through unimpeachable integrity and solid competence.
