These are not Warhol&#39;s boxes
Anyone who associates the terms Sweden and wooden box thinks of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden are currently casting dark shadows on Warhol&#39;s catalog raisonné.
Most of the ninety-four &quot;Stockholm type&quot; Brillo boxes listed there are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper &quot;Expressen&quot; raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol&#39;s Brillo boxes from 1968 a few months ago, internal investigations at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm have now come to a sobering conclusion: the six &quot;Brillo boxes&quot; that the former museum director Pontus Hultén donated to the Moderna Museet in 1995 are copies - and probably also the majority of the approximately one hundred other Brillo boxes of the &quot;Stockholm type&quot; that are in circulation on the international art market.
The history is convoluted, a confusing concatenation of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 in New York, Warhol created his first &quot;Brillo-Boxes&quot;, painted wooden boxes based on the red, blue and white design of the cardboard boxes of the &quot;Brillo&quot; soap powder.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 exhibited - with Warhol&#39;s consent - hundreds of Brillo cardboard boxes: These did not come from Warhol (for reasons of cost) but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard box factory.
These were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably gave permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, although these were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes that rightly went down in art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation &quot;Type Stockholm&quot;.
Some of them have fetched more than $100,000 at auction.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then gave him.
In fact, Hultén&#39;s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that point, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at Moderna Museet, examined the six Brillo boxes belonging to the museum as well as three privately owned Swedish boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their chipboard panels were first primed and sanded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the chipboard with a paint roller without a primer - moreover, it is not oil paint but acrylic paint.
&quot;These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol&#39;s Brillo boxes,&quot; says Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: &quot;If the &#39;Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board&#39; in New York does not comes to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six cases in its collection as copies/exhibition material.&quot;
In July, however, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the &quot;serious allegations&quot; made about the soap powder boxes.
But since then, there has been a relentless silence.
